{{For|the metalworking process|Burnishing (metal)}}
{{unreferenced|date=March 2011}}

'''Burnishing''' is a form of [[pottery]] treatment in which the surface of the pot is [[Polishing|polished]], using a hard smooth surface such as a wooden or bone spatula, smooth stones, plastic, or even glass bulbs, while it still is in a leathery 'green' state, i.e., before [[Pottery#Firing|firing]]. After firing, the surface is extremely shiny. Often the whole outer surface of the pot is thus decorated, but in certain [[ceramic]] traditions there is 'pattern burnishing' where the outside and, in the case of open bowls, the inside, are decorated with burnished patterns in which some areas are left [[Gloss (paint)|matte]].

This technique can be applied to [[Concrete masonry unit|concrete masonry]], creating a polished [[Surface finishing|finish]]. 

Burnishing can also be applied to wood, by rubbing two pieces together along the [[Wood grain|grain]]. Hard woods take the treatment best.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Burnishing does not protect the wood like a [[varnish]] does, but does impart a glossy sheen.

If one wood has a [[dye]] in it or is colored in some way, it may rub off onto the other wood. Burnishing can also apply to [[relief printing]].

